content.description: Climb slabby hourglass shaped fin past a bolt into shallow grooves. Continue up past a second bolt and onto the vegetated headwall. Standard rack to #4 cam.
content.location: Just left of the large crack in the middle of the wall.

content.description: Up the corner and then trend R to a crack "system" (of sorts) to attain the summit. There is more than one option for the exit, but look for the anchor up and R. You might not be able to see it at first, as it is back a bit. Either rap off the anchor (I used a skinny 50m and had plenty of thread left) or hunt for a discontinuous ledge system far to climber's R, then hook back around the right back to the base. Rapping is best/easiest).
content.protection: Standard rack including 3" cam (per K Keith's excellent guidebook)
content.location: On the far L side (the "trail" should dump you out right in front of it) of the formation is a L-facing corner. You found it...!

content.protection: Multiple fatties and your best, most objective judgement of your personal skill level. Keith says "standard rack up to #4 cam". I say - cast your eyeballs upon it, heathen.
content.location: R of Second Trimester in the approximate center of the formation.

content.description: Hardly a dome... this formation is north facing and host a few scrappy routes that are fun. Routes are mixed bolts and gear.It's possible, though not preferable, to descend on the far right down a series of ledge-like affairs and then continuing to hook back around to the right down a gully and, eventually, back to the launch area. Better to rap off the anchor on Dirty Laundry/Night Moves.
